<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-232-258  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 232 258.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  March 12 1990 v7 n10 p53(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft, Novell pledge new Named Pipes efforts. (Microsoft Corp.andO;and Novell Inc. revive Named Pipes programming interface for OS/2LAN Manager)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pallatto, John.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Microsoft Corp and Novell Inc have revived development efforts onthe Named Pipes application programming interface in order toallow DOS workstations running under NetWare to access SQL Serverunder OS/2 LAN Manager.andP;  The companies are giving in to pressurefrom corporate developers, who say they need Named Pipes supportin NetWare in order to create SQL applications.andP;  Officials atMicrosoft say they will take an active role in resolving the NamedPipes 'gap' in NetWare, a reversal of the company's quashing ajoint Novell/Ashton-Tate project to port SQL Server to NetWare.andO;Large corporations say that Named Pipes support will determinewhich relational DBMS server they will use.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product development)Novell Inc. (product development).andO;Ticker:    NOVL; MSFT.andO;Topic:     Network Management SoftwareApplications ProgrammingInterfaceProduct DevelopmentStructured Query LanguageData Base ServersMS-DOSOS-2Compatibility.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John PallattoandM;Pressure from corporate developers has forced Microsoft Corp. and Novell Inc.andO;to step up their efforts to allow DOS workstations running under NetWare toaccess OS/2 SQL Server, officials from both companies recently acknowledged.andM;Developers are clamoring for support in DOS NetWare for Microsoft's NamedPipes programming interface for OS/2 LAN Manager.andP;  Such support would letthem design front-end applications that give the huge installed base of DOSPCs access to the emerging crop of OS/2-based network programs --particularly Microsoft's SQL Server database, they said.andM;&quot;It is a very urgent issue -- it is one of the things that inhibits us fromusing SQL Server,&quot; said Michael Dermer, a programmer/ analyst at DukeUniversity in Durham, N.C.andP;  &quot;Most of our users work with NetWare, and wedon't want to have to purchase OS/2 for all of them if they are just going tooccasionally query the database server.&quot;andM;Microsoft officials said last month at an SQL Server conference that the firmwould take a more active role in resolving the lack of DOS Named Pipessupport in NetWare.andP;  &quot;We will either do it ourselves or work with a thirdparty&quot; to develop and test such connectivity, said Dwayne Walker, SQL Serverproduct manager at Microsoft in Redmond, Wash.andM;This new commitment marks a virtual about-face for Microsoft in itsrecognition of NetWare as a key platform for its OS/2-based databasesoftware.andP;  In September 1988, Microsoft reportedly quashed a planned jointdevelopment project between Novell and Ashton-Tate -- then a partner in SQLServer -- intended to port the database to NetWare.andM;Walker said that Microsoft would provide technical assistance to Novell todeliver this capability, as it did when the two firms worked together todeliver Named Pipes support for NetWare for OS/2.andM;DOS Named Pipes support has not been one of the top priorities at Novell,said Darrell Miller, executive vice president for Novell's Software Group inProvo, Utah.andP;  However, the firm is now &quot;freeing resources from other[projects] and working on it,&quot; he said.andP;  Miller declined to provide adelivery date for DOS Named Pipes.andM;The Named Pipes issue for DOS NetWare may determine which relational databaseserver is used at Aetna Life Insurance Co.'s Personal Financial SecurityDivision, said Hal Whitney, a technology advisor to the Hartford, Conn.,andO;division.andM;&quot;Aetna has decided that NetWare is going to be the operating system ofchoice,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;If SQL Server can't communicate with DOS workstationsunder NetWare, Aetna will have to consider other servers.&quot;andM;----------Additional reporting by Jane Morrissey</TEXT></DOC>